record. This book examines the process of purge and rehabilitation of memory in the person of Virius Nicomachus Flavianus(?-394). Charles Hedrick describes how Flavian was condemned for participating in the rebellion against the Christian emperor Theodosius the Great—and then restored to the public record a generation later as members of the newly Christianized senatorial class sought to reconcile their pagan past and Christian present. By selectively remembering and forgetting the actions of Flavian, Hedrick asserts, the Roman elite honored their ancestors while participating in profound social, cultural, and religious change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aElite (Social sciences)zItalyzRomexHistoriography. 0aInscriptions, LatinzItalyzRome. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszItalyzRomexHistory. 0aMonumentsxConservation and restorationzItalyzRomexHistory. 0aPalimpsestszItalyzRome. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73121940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799158423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799158/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK